Disk diffusion is assessed by measuring the diameters of zones of growth inhibition on tested microorganism and the results are presented as shown in Table 3
                     . The diameter of the zone of inhibition for ZnO NPs against Staphylococcus aureus, Enterococcus faecalis, MRSA, Escherichia coli, Shigella dysenteriae and VRE are about 19, 12, 11, 10, 8 and 8 mm respectively. It can be seen from the table that Staphylococcus aureus has an Inhibition growth zone higher than other tested microorganisms (Fig. 11
                     ). However, no inhibitory effect was observed on Klebsiella pneumonia, Proteus vulgaris, Pseudomonas aeruginosa, and Acinetobacter pneumonia. Also, findings demonstrated that ZnO/CQDs NCs no inhibitory effect against tested bacteria (Fig. 12
                     ). According to previously reported papers, the exact mechanism of the antibacterial activity of ZnO NPs is not clear and still controversial [31,32]. In general, three mechanisms can be proposed for antibacterial activity of ZnO NPs: ⅰ) release of reactive oxygen species (ROS) from the surface of ZnO NPs which can lead to damage DNA, cell membranes, and cellular proteins, ⅱ) release of Zn2+ ions which can damage the cell membrane and penetrate the intracellular contents, and ⅲ) direct contact of ZnO NPs with cell walls which can be lead to bacteria cell destruction [7]. It is obvious that in three proposed mechanisms, the surface of ZnO NPs plays a crucial role in antibacterial activity. In the ZnO/CQDs NCs case, CQDs have a knock-on effect on the antibacterial activity of ZnO NPs. In another word, the CQDs was inextricably bound up with the surface of ZnO NPs and led to significant declining of bacteria cell destruction. Furthermore, the CQDs can disrupt the release of Zn2+ ions (ⅱ) and direct contact (ⅲ) routes. The formed CQDs have a hydroxyl and carboxyl-rich surface that can prevent their binding to bacteria with negative surface charge and cause the antibacterial activity to plummet [33]. The schematic mechanism of ZnO NPs and ZnO/CQDs NCs is provided in Fig. 13
                     . The present result (antibacterial test) is compared with previously published papers in Table 4
                     .
